Spring Data Access:
  Data Access layer provides a consistent way to interact with databases.

Why Spring Data Access?
Before Spring :
      JDBC → too much boilerplate
      Hibernate → complex setup
      Different APIs for each technology
Spring solves this by:
      Providing uniform abstraction
      Reducing boilerplate code
      Handling exceptions consistently
Internal Architecture:
      Controller → Service (@Transactional) → DAO / Repository → Spring Data / ORM → JDBC → Database
Modules in Spring Data Access:
  1. JDBC Module - Simplifies JDBC operations
     Key Class :JdbcTemplate
    jdbcTemplate.query("SELECT * FROM user", (rs, rowNum) -> new User(rs.getString("name")));
    ✔ Features: Removes boilerplate, Handles connection closing and Exception handling
    Use Case: Simple queries and Performance-critical apps
  2.ORM Module - Integrates ORM frameworks like: JPA, Hiberante and myBatis
    Purpose :Object ↔ Table mapping and Reduce SQL usage
    Features : Session management, Lazy loading and Caching
    Use Case: Complex domain models and Enterprise applications
    JPA:
        JPA (Java Persistence API) is a specification (set of rules/interfaces) for ORM.
        Key Idea : ✔ JPA defines what should be done and ❌ It does NOT provide implementation
        @Entity
        public class User {
            @Id
            private Long id;
            private String name;
        }
        EntityManager em = ...;
        User user = em.find(User.class, 1L);
        Key Components : EntityManager , @Entity , @Id and JPQL (query language)
        ✔ Advantage :Decouples your code from ORM tool
     Hibernate:
        Hibernate is an ORM framework (implementation).
        Key Idea: ✔ Hibernate implements JPA and ✔ Also provides extra features
        Session session = sessionFactory.openSession();
        User user = session.get(User.class, 1);
        Key Components :Session and SessionFactory and HQL (Hibernate Query Language)
        ✔ Features: Automatic SQL generation , Caching (1st & 2nd level) , Lazy loading  and Dirty checking
    
    Hibernate vs JPA 
      Feature	          JPA	            Hibernate
      Type	            Specification	  Implementation
      Dependency	      Interface	      Framework
      Portability	      High	          Low
      Extra Features   	No	            Yes
      Query	            JPQL	          HQL + JPQL
  Relationship (Core Concept):
        JPA → Specification
        Hibernate → Implementation of JPA
   Real Flow
            Your Code →JPA (EntityManager) → Hibernate → JDBC → Database
  Important Concepts in Hibernate & JPA
  1. ORM (Object Relational Mapping)
    Java Object ↔ Database Table
            Java    	DB
            Class	    Table
            Object	  Row
            Field    	Column
  2. Entity Lifecycle
          State	        Meaning
          Transient	    New object
          Persistent	  Managed by session
          Detached	    Not managed
          Removed	      Deleted
 3. Fetch Types
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
      Type	Meaning
      Lazy	Load when needed
      Eager	Load immediately
  4. Caching
      First-Level Cache - ✔ Session-level ✔ Always enabled
      Second-Level Cache - ✔ Shared across sessions ✔ Optional
  5. Dirty Checking - Hibernate automatically detects changes: user.setName("New"); ✔ No need for update query
  6. Query Types: 
    JPQL (JPA) -SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.name = :name
    HQL (Hibernate) - ✔ Similar to JPQL ✔ Hibernate-specific extensions
    Native SQL -SELECT * FROM users
  
   Common Problems:
  ❗ N+1 Problem- Multiple queries due to lazy loading
  ❗ LazyInitializationException- Access lazy data outside session
  
  What is “Criteria” in ORM?
    Criteria = a programmatic way to build queries dynamically (instead of writing SQL/JPQL strings)
  Why use Criteria?
      Dynamic queries (conditions at runtime)
      Avoid string-based queries
      Type-safe (in modern API)
  Types of Criteria:
         Old: Hibernate Criteria (Deprecated)
        Criteria c = session.createCriteria(User.class);
        c.add(Restrictions.eq("name", "Baskar"));👉 Deprecated ❌
        Modern: JPA Criteria API
        From JPA
        
        CriteriaBuilder cb = em.getCriteriaBuilder();
        CriteriaQuery<User> cq = cb.createQuery(User.class);
        
        Root<User> root = cq.from(User.class);
        cq.select(root).where(cb.equal(root.get("name"), "Baskar"));
        
        List<User> users = em.createQuery(cq).getResultList();
  
  Key Idea (Important):
   Criteria is part of ORM querying mechanism
   Used for dynamic and complex queries

  What is SessionFactory?
   Factory that creates Session objects
   Key Characteristics: Heavy-weight object ⚠️, Created once per application and Thread-safe ✅
   Holds: DB configuration ,Mapping metadata and 2nd level cache
        SessionFactory factory = new Configuration()
            .configure()
            .buildSessionFactory();
  ✔ Responsibilities: Create sessions, Maintain cache and Store ORM mappings

  What is Session?
    Connection between application and database
    Key Characteristics: Light-weight object, Created per request/transaction and NOT thread-safe ❌ and Represents persistence context
    Session session = factory.openSession();
    
    User user = session.get(User.class, 1);
    ✔ Responsibilities: CRUD operations, Manage entity lifecycle, First-level cache and Dirty checking
    What happens if Session not closed? ❌ Memory leak
    Session Lifecycle: OpenSession() → perform operations → flush() → close()

   Session Management -  Managing session lifecycle automatically

    ❌ Without Spring
    Session session = factory.openSession();
    Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();
    
    session.save(user);
    
    tx.commit();
    session.close();

    ✅ With Spring (Best Practice)
    @Transactional
    public void saveUser() {
        repository.save(user);
    }
   How Spring Manages Session
      Uses ThreadLocal
      Binds session to transaction
      Auto open/close session
   Open Session in View (OSIV)-  Keeps session open till view rendering
    ✔ Avoids LazyInitializationException
    ❌ Can cause performance issues

    What replaces these in JPA?
    Hibernate          	JPA
    SessionFactory	    EntityManagerFactory
    Session            	EntityManager

    EntityManager: main interface to interact with persistence context
                  @PersistenceContext
                  private EntityManager em;
    ✔ Responsibilities: CRUD operations, Manage entity lifecycle and Execute queries and Handle persistence context
      Common Methods
                    em.persist(user);     // insert
                    em.find(User.class, 1); // select
                    em.merge(user);       // update
                    em.remove(user);      // delete
    
    EntityManagerFactory: Factory that creates EntityManager
     Key Points: Heavy object ⚠️, Created once per application and Thread-safe ✅
              EntityManagerFactory emf =
                  Persistence.createEntityManagerFactory("myUnit");
      Relationship : EntityManagerFactory → creates → EntityManager → interacts with DB
    
    Persistence Context (Important 🔥) - Managed by EntityManager ✔ Stores managed entities ✔ Acts like cache

   flush() Method - Synchronizes persistence context → database
            em.persist(user);
            em.flush();
  Behavior:Executes SQL immediately, Does NOT commit transaction
  When flush happens automatically? Before query execution and Before transaction commit
  Important: flush != commit ✔ Flush → send SQL ✔ Commit → save permanently

   clear() Method- Removes all entities from persistence context
            em.clear();
    Effect:
          All entities become detached
          No tracking (no dirty checking)

        User user = em.find(User.class, 1);
        em.clear();
        user.setName("New"); // NOT updated in DB
  flush() vs clear()
  Feature	      flush()    	clear()
  Purpose	      Sync DB	    Clear cache
  SQL execution	Yes	        No
  Entity state	Managed	    Detached
  
  Full Flow (Important) : EntityManagerFactory → EntityManager → Persistence Context →flush() →DB

  Entity Class Annotations (Mapping)

These annotations map Java objects ↔ Database tables
   @Entity - ✔ Marks class as a persistent entity ✔ Must have a primary key
   @Table - ✔ Maps class to specific table ✔ Optional (default = class name)
   @Id -✔ Primary key
   @GeneratedValue - @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY) ✔ Auto-generates ID
     Strategies:
      IDENTITY (DB auto increment)
      SEQUENCE
      TABLE
      AUTO
   @Column -@Column(name = "user_name", nullable = false) ✔ Maps field → column ✔ Controls: name, nullable,length
   @Transient - ✔ Not persisted in DB
   @Lob - ✔ Large objects (BLOB/CLOB)
